<p>If it's reasonable to do so?  Maybe a modified 1?:</p>
<ol>
<li>Hire a replacement now, let the employee bring them up to speed. <strong>Arrange so they have different duties that only overlap in the area you want redundancy.</strong> Then terminate the problematic employee.</li>
</ol>
<p>If you want to transfer knowledge you need to create only a reasonable amount of redundancy.  The problem being this probably takes twice as long as first you need to change their duties.  You might even find they improve with changed duties.</p>
