<div class="answercell post-layout--right">
    
    <div class="s-prose js-post-body" itemprop="text">
<p>Let the employee work from home. If they keep coming in, your other employees will riot from having to deal with an asshole. If they get to WFH, your other employees will riot from the asshole getting special treatment. Fortunately, in the second case, you can make an announcement over the loudspeaker and say &quot;the employee isn't getting special treatment, they're in time out until we find their replacement.&quot;</p>
<p>Next, assign them a junior. Assholes love to boss people around. I'd start the junior at, like, $135k. Maybe more. You gotta pay them enough that they can't, in good conscience, leave. The younger the better -- a 24 year old will just assume that toxic workplaces are the norm -- and then they'll go and buy a house. Once they have a mortgage, they're fucking stuck.</p>
<p>The bottom line is that the asshole will boss around the junior and make them do the annoying bullshit. The junior will find ways to untangle the annoying bullshit. In a year, the junior will have untangled practically your entire system... and built an even more tangled one... but the difference will be that you coach the junior constantly on the value of documentation. So at least their mess will be written down. Then you fire the asshole, make the junior a senior, and give the senior a new junior. Repeat as necessary when that guy becomes an asshole from working in a toxic environment for years.</p>
<p>This plan only works if a proper manager assigns the pair a roadmap. Don't micromanage them, and don't over-task them. Your success relies on the junior having downtime to be like &quot;hey, remember how we used to have to maintain this piece of legacy tech? I've replaced it. Can we deploy it now?&quot;</p>
    </div>
